1
00:00:00,309 --> 00:00:05,570
What if I told you the big banks and hedge
funds can actually control the markets?

2
00:00:05,570 --> 00:00:11,559
And that with a little observation, you could
easily spot their moves before anyone else.

3
00:00:11,559 --> 00:00:14,290
Volume price analysis is the answer.

4
00:00:14,290 --> 00:00:18,930
The volume price analysis is based on the
idea that big players like banks and hedge

5
00:00:18,930 --> 00:00:22,700
funds manipulate the market behind the scenes.

6
00:00:22,700 --> 00:00:27,590
Once you accept that, you can assume that
these big players know where the market is

7
00:00:27,590 --> 00:00:30,180
going before anyone else.

8
00:00:30,180 --> 00:00:34,379
If that's true, then all you need to do is
follow their moves.

9
00:00:34,379 --> 00:00:38,340
You want to buy what they're buying and sell
what they're selling.

10
00:00:38,340 --> 00:00:43,860
And when they're not actively participating,
you should stay out of the market too.

11
00:00:43,860 --> 00:00:47,010
So these are the simple concepts behind this
trading method.

12
00:00:47,010 --> 00:00:52,570
And we can see what the big players are doing
by paying attention to price and volume.

13
00:00:52,570 --> 00:00:58,079
Basically, even though these big traders try
to hide their moves, there's one thing they

14
00:00:58,079 --> 00:01:00,490
can't hide - the volume.

15
00:01:00,490 --> 00:01:05,420
Since they handle such huge amounts of money,
it's obvious when they're getting into or

16
00:01:05,420 --> 00:01:09,020
out of a market because the volume will increase.

17
00:01:09,020 --> 00:01:15,630
On the other hand, if the price jumps but
the volume stays low, that usually means the

18
00:01:15,630 --> 00:01:20,930
big traders are just manipulating the market
but not actually putting in any real money

19
00:01:20,930 --> 00:01:22,150
themselves.

20
00:01:22,150 --> 00:01:25,930
So you have to be careful of traps in those
cases.

21
00:01:25,930 --> 00:01:30,940
Only by keeping an eye on both price and volume
together, you can read what those banks and

22
00:01:30,940 --> 00:01:32,479
hedge funds are up to.

23
00:01:32,479 --> 00:01:37,710
And once you know where they're putting their
money to work, you've got a good idea of where

24
00:01:37,710 --> 00:01:40,700
the market is likely headed next.

25
00:01:40,700 --> 00:01:47,000
This Volume Price Analysis (VPA) method was
developed by Richard Wyckoff back in the day.

26
00:01:47,000 --> 00:01:50,619
He came up with three main laws that it's
based on.

27
00:01:50,619 --> 00:01:53,250
First law is about effort and result.

28
00:01:53,250 --> 00:01:59,290
Basically, it means the volume, or effort,
needs to match up with the price move, or

29
00:01:59,290 --> 00:02:00,490
result.

30
00:02:00,490 --> 00:02:04,890
So if volume is high, you should see a big
change in price.

31
00:02:04,890 --> 00:02:08,140
If they don't line up, something ain't right.

32
00:02:08,140 --> 00:02:13,620
You can use anomalies between volume and price
to figure out if the big players are buying

33
00:02:13,620 --> 00:02:14,620
or selling.

34
00:02:14,620 --> 00:02:18,170
We’ll talk about them later in the video.

35
00:02:18,170 --> 00:02:21,300
Wyckoff's second law is about cause and effect.

36
00:02:21,300 --> 00:02:23,000
Basically, about time.

37
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:28,170
If they take a long time to build up a new
move, you can expect the resulting price change

38
00:02:28,170 --> 00:02:31,190
to be large too when it happens.

39
00:02:31,190 --> 00:02:37,640
The final law is supply and demand - if supply
is greater than demand, price will drop.

40
00:02:37,640 --> 00:02:42,330
But if demand is bigger than supply, then
price goes up.

41
00:02:42,330 --> 00:02:48,610
These three laws explain how price is always
rotating between bull and bear markets over

42
00:02:48,610 --> 00:02:50,879
different time periods.

43
00:02:50,879 --> 00:02:54,530
And volume helps uncover what the big money
are doing.

44
00:02:54,530 --> 00:03:00,450
This trading cycle follows the same pattern
no matter what time frame you look at, whether

45
00:03:00,450 --> 00:03:02,970
it's a 1 minute chart or 1 month chart.

46
00:03:02,970 --> 00:03:07,720
Of course, you have the odds in your favor
when you’re analyzing higher time frames.

47
00:03:07,720 --> 00:03:11,640
I prefer to monitor the daily chart when I’m
analyzing volume.

48
00:03:11,640 --> 00:03:18,061
It’s easier this way, 1 candle means 1 trading
day, and it has more meaning than 1-min time

49
00:03:18,061 --> 00:03:19,061
frame.

50
00:03:19,061 --> 00:03:25,610
Now, a full rotation between market phases
happens from the selling climax up to the

51
00:03:25,610 --> 00:03:29,049
buying climax and back down again.

52
00:03:29,049 --> 00:03:34,069
When I talk about a buying climax, that's
when these big players are starting selling

53
00:03:34,069 --> 00:03:36,349
near the top of a rally.

54
00:03:36,349 --> 00:03:41,459
The selling climax is when they're start buying
at the bottom of a drop.

55
00:03:41,459 --> 00:03:47,550
At the buying climax, the market has been
moving up so long that little guys are terrified

56
00:03:47,550 --> 00:03:48,950
of missing out.

57
00:03:48,950 --> 00:03:54,800
Eventually they cave and jump in right as
the big players start their selling into a

58
00:03:54,800 --> 00:03:56,640
weakening market.

59
00:03:56,640 --> 00:04:01,320
Volatile price action and news are used to
dump their positions.

60
00:04:01,320 --> 00:04:07,670
FOMO, or fear of missing out, is a powerful
emotion the big traders use to their full

61
00:04:07,670 --> 00:04:13,670
advantage getting the little retail guys to
buy at highs.

62
00:04:13,670 --> 00:04:18,980
Once their positions are cleared, they start
planning the next phase.

63
00:04:18,980 --> 00:04:24,350
The selling climax happens when the big money
players need to refill their positions.

64
00:04:24,350 --> 00:04:31,120
At this point, fear of losing money triggers
everyone else to bail their positions.

65
00:04:31,120 --> 00:04:36,759
Quickly, the big players crash the price down
usually because of some news.

66
00:04:36,759 --> 00:04:42,419
Then retail traders panic sell right into
the big guys' buy orders.

67
00:04:42,419 --> 00:04:49,009
Once they've accumulated enough, the big guys
jump in to stop the market from falling further.

68
00:04:49,009 --> 00:04:52,480
And then a next phase begins.

69
00:04:52,480 --> 00:04:56,990
This also explains why markets drop faster
than they rise.

70
00:04:56,990 --> 00:05:02,580
Smart money have all the time in the world
to let prices rise to make their big profits.

71
00:05:02,580 --> 00:05:04,539
They actually plan everything out.

72
00:05:04,539 --> 00:05:11,150
The worst thing would be getting overwhelmed
by too much buying or selling early, wrecking

73
00:05:11,150 --> 00:05:12,820
their new plan.

74
00:05:12,820 --> 00:05:16,949
That's why before starting a new campaign,
they run a quick test.

75
00:05:16,949 --> 00:05:22,980
Once the big accumulation phase finishes at
the sellling climax, before they launch their

76
00:05:22,980 --> 00:05:26,100
new campaign, they run a quick test.

77
00:05:26,100 --> 00:05:30,660
This makes sure any leftover sellers have
been soaked up.

78
00:05:30,660 --> 00:05:37,130
Doing so ensures the upcoming bull run can
unfold smoothly without any major sellers

79
00:05:37,130 --> 00:05:38,730
pulling it down.

80
00:05:38,730 --> 00:05:44,080
The test involves a small downward price push,
below support.

81
00:05:44,080 --> 00:05:46,240
Volume staying low confirms it.

82
00:05:46,240 --> 00:05:48,280
They call it a "supply test".

83
00:05:48,280 --> 00:05:53,440
If it passes with low volume, their next buying
campaign has the green light.

84
00:05:53,440 --> 00:06:00,820
Similarly, at the end of the big rally (buying
climax), a "demand test" happens before the

85
00:06:00,820 --> 00:06:02,250
bearish campaign.

86
00:06:02,250 --> 00:06:09,139
The big guys briefly send it higher, often
times above resistance – and no extra demand

87
00:06:09,139 --> 00:06:11,960
means it will fail back with ease.

88
00:06:11,960 --> 00:06:15,050
This confirms no major buyers are around.

89
00:06:15,050 --> 00:06:21,030
So, the whole premise of understanding the
volume price analysis is accepting the big

90
00:06:21,030 --> 00:06:25,320
players control and manipulate everything
behind the scenes.

91
00:06:25,320 --> 00:06:31,460
The only thing we need to know is when they're
actively buying, selling or sitting out a

92
00:06:31,460 --> 00:06:32,460
move.

93
00:06:32,460 --> 00:06:38,690
In my approach, watching each daily candle,
monitoring price changes and volume, helps

94
00:06:38,690 --> 00:06:44,880
me with that, by looking if those two factors
sync up or contradict each other.

95
00:06:44,880 --> 00:06:50,080
If the price and volume are high, then the
big players are steering things and are in

96
00:06:50,080 --> 00:06:52,040
the driver's seat.

97
00:06:52,040 --> 00:06:55,419
But if they are in disagreement, things are
suspect.

98
00:06:55,419 --> 00:07:01,699
One of the most important areas on the price
chart is when a market is in congestion, as

99
00:07:01,699 --> 00:07:10,350
markets spend 70% to 80% of their time in
such regions, and only 20% of the time trending.

100
00:07:10,350 --> 00:07:16,080
It's real simple - these are the areas where
new moves are cooked up by the big players

101
00:07:16,080 --> 00:07:19,560
planning for the next part of their plan.

102
00:07:19,560 --> 00:07:26,539
Could be huge areas like right before a big
sell-off or rally, or even maybe smaller moves

103
00:07:26,539 --> 00:07:31,500
where a market has paused in the primary trend.

104
00:07:31,500 --> 00:07:36,599
Understanding congestion phases along with
support and resistance or supply and demand

105
00:07:36,599 --> 00:07:39,780
is a key element of volume price analysis.

106
00:07:39,780 --> 00:07:45,139
And many traders don't get it or ignore it
trying to chase trends all the time.

107
00:07:45,139 --> 00:07:50,789
The longer a market remains at a price level,
then the greater the concentration of volume,

108
00:07:50,789 --> 00:07:56,500
and price will only continue to move on, once
the balance of bearish or bullish sentiment

109
00:07:56,500 --> 00:07:57,950
shifts.

110
00:07:57,950 --> 00:08:03,760
And whenever a breakout happens, volume tells
you if it's a real move or fake news.

111
00:08:03,760 --> 00:08:09,610
So, support and resistance levels, supply
and demand and price action must be part of

112
00:08:09,610 --> 00:08:12,590
this volume analysis.

113
00:08:12,590 --> 00:08:17,550
This example shows a wide range candle over
one trading day.

114
00:08:17,550 --> 00:08:19,830
Volume was way above normal.

115
00:08:19,830 --> 00:08:24,210
So the trading activity backed up the price
movement that day.

116
00:08:24,210 --> 00:08:30,169
For a move to be real, the effort to push
it higher should be seen in the volume.

117
00:08:30,169 --> 00:08:36,290
That's Wyckoff's third law - it takes effort
to drive prices up or down, so a big daily

118
00:08:36,290 --> 00:08:40,880
change means heavy trading volume backing
it up.

119
00:08:40,880 --> 00:08:43,090
And that's exactly what we got here.

120
00:08:43,090 --> 00:08:47,920
Therefore, the volume validates the price
action as genuine.

121
00:08:47,920 --> 00:08:53,130
So the move wasn't secretly manipulated by
big players or market makers.

122
00:08:53,130 --> 00:08:58,850
And for now, the trend is still bullish since
we don't see anything telling us otherwise

123
00:08:58,850 --> 00:09:00,970
yet.

124
00:09:00,970 --> 00:09:06,400
This chart shows a narrow body candle with
wicks on top and bottom.

125
00:09:06,400 --> 00:09:09,660
Trading volume was way below average too.

126
00:09:09,660 --> 00:09:15,760
Even though the price rose a bit, the move
was really small so the candle is narrow.

127
00:09:15,760 --> 00:09:19,110
Volume backing it up is also low.

128
00:09:19,110 --> 00:09:24,210
That's because of Wyckoff's law again - effort
and result need to match up.

129
00:09:24,210 --> 00:09:30,119
If the price only increased a bit (the result),
then volume (the effort) shouldn't be heavy.

130
00:09:30,119 --> 00:09:36,279
So once more, the volume confirms that what
we're seeing with price action is real.

131
00:09:36,279 --> 00:09:41,100
A small daily price increase implies slim
trading activity.

132
00:09:41,100 --> 00:09:47,750
Volume is still validating the price movement
as genuinely reflecting what's happening behind

133
00:09:47,750 --> 00:09:50,140
the scenes.

134
00:09:50,140 --> 00:09:55,270
Here we see a wide candle, so the volume should
match that big move.

135
00:09:55,270 --> 00:10:02,370
Instead, volume is low even though price had
a wide range - and this is a divergence!

136
00:10:02,370 --> 00:10:08,220
A large daily candle body usually means heavy
trading to push it there.

137
00:10:08,220 --> 00:10:10,840
But a low volume bar doesn't add up.

138
00:10:10,840 --> 00:10:17,120
If I was already in a long position and saw
this, I'd start questioning the move.

139
00:10:17,120 --> 00:10:18,630
Could it be a trap forming?

140
00:10:18,630 --> 00:10:25,490
You will see that this divergence pattern
often shows up at the start of equity sessions.

141
00:10:25,490 --> 00:10:31,980
Basically the big money is feeling out sentiment
in the market by shooting price up to test

142
00:10:31,980 --> 00:10:33,860
buyer interest.

143
00:10:33,860 --> 00:10:35,870
But again, the move was fake.

144
00:10:35,870 --> 00:10:43,040
It's designed to trick traders into weak longs
and hit their stop losses before price reverses

145
00:10:43,040 --> 00:10:44,269
hard.

146
00:10:44,269 --> 00:10:50,110
That's why VSA is so powerful - volume reveals
the truth behind prices.

147
00:10:50,110 --> 00:10:58,280
It unmasks the intentions of big players setting
traps versus real momentum shifts.

148
00:10:58,280 --> 00:11:03,970
Now we see a narrow candle range but massive
volume, which is another mixed signal.

149
00:11:03,970 --> 00:11:09,290
By Wyckoff's law, a small price move should
need low volume, but that's not happening

150
00:11:09,290 --> 00:11:10,440
here.

151
00:11:10,440 --> 00:11:15,850
There's really only one way to read this - the
market is starting to look suspect.

152
00:11:15,850 --> 00:11:22,190
Patterns like these often show up at turning
points, like tops of price increases or bottoms

153
00:11:22,190 --> 00:11:23,889
of down moves.

154
00:11:23,889 --> 00:11:30,769
For example, in an established bullish phase,
price rises a bit at the open but then the

155
00:11:30,769 --> 00:11:34,160
big boys start cashing out their gains.

156
00:11:34,160 --> 00:11:39,720
More buyers hop in, but price stops going
up since the smart money are selling into

157
00:11:39,720 --> 00:11:43,510
them and pocketing profits at this level.

158
00:11:43,510 --> 00:11:49,810
What's actually happening is this price can't
keep rising no matter how many buyers jump

159
00:11:49,810 --> 00:11:54,750
in because the smart money are constantly
selling to take profits.

160
00:11:54,750 --> 00:12:00,899
So when price and volume tell different stories
like this, it's signaling underlying weakness

161
00:12:00,899 --> 00:12:03,750
in the overall trend.

162
00:12:03,750 --> 00:12:08,820
Here we see a rising market with prices following
volume higher.

163
00:12:08,820 --> 00:12:11,650
That's exactly the sync we want to see.

164
00:12:11,650 --> 00:12:18,149
The first candle has a small range and volume
is low, matching the little price move.

165
00:12:18,149 --> 00:12:19,900
No issues there.

166
00:12:19,900 --> 00:12:24,410
The second candle is wider so its volume should
be greater.

167
00:12:24,410 --> 00:12:28,700
And yes, volume increased along with price
action.

168
00:12:28,700 --> 00:12:35,280
By the third candle's even bigger daily range,
its volume needs to be really strong.

169
00:12:35,280 --> 00:12:39,420
Once again, trading activity backed up the
result.

170
00:12:39,420 --> 00:12:43,830
Price action on the candles has been validated
by the volume.

171
00:12:43,830 --> 00:12:50,149
Price increased higher over the period while
volume increased with it each step of the

172
00:12:50,149 --> 00:12:51,149
way.

173
00:12:51,149 --> 00:12:57,220
Everything is lining up between effort and
result - bullish price action reinforced by

174
00:12:57,220 --> 00:12:59,490
heavy buying volume.

175
00:12:59,490 --> 00:13:02,180
This is the ideal trend validation.

176
00:13:02,180 --> 00:13:10,209
In this example, we see a confirmed uptrend
starting with a small candle on low volume

177
00:13:10,209 --> 00:13:12,209
as expected.

178
00:13:12,209 --> 00:13:18,340
The second candle's range increased a bit
but volume was higher compared to the tiny

179
00:13:18,340 --> 00:13:20,260
price action.

180
00:13:20,260 --> 00:13:26,470
That's a divergence - a small price move shouldn't
pump volume that much.

181
00:13:26,470 --> 00:13:31,920
Candle no. three was wider but volume decreased
versus the big move before.

182
00:13:31,920 --> 00:13:37,630
It should've been higher too with the bigger
daily price change.

183
00:13:37,630 --> 00:13:39,110
Another warning.

184
00:13:39,110 --> 00:13:44,820
Then candle four was a wide range one, yet
volume dropped again.

185
00:13:44,820 --> 00:13:47,639
Multiple mixed signals stacking up now.

186
00:13:47,639 --> 00:13:52,610
A wide price swing shouldn't have volume declining
more.

187
00:13:52,610 --> 00:13:56,610
Falling volume conflicts with the ongoing
bullish run.

188
00:13:56,610 --> 00:14:00,839
We have several divergence problems in this
supposed trend.

189
00:14:00,839 --> 00:14:06,449
Things are no longer lining up like they should
between effort and result.

190
00:14:06,449 --> 00:14:12,100
I hope you see how price alone can only tell
you what a market’s present technical position

191
00:14:12,100 --> 00:14:18,500
really is, but not where the trend is probably
headed, at least not accurately.

192
00:14:18,500 --> 00:14:24,490
Volume helps to validate the trend with more
accuracy and also detects turning points,

193
00:14:24,490 --> 00:14:27,060
when to open or close trades.

194
00:14:27,060 --> 00:14:30,420
And together, they form a complete picture.

195
00:14:30,420 --> 00:14:33,970
Price must go hand in hand with volume.

196
00:14:33,970 --> 00:14:38,040
Is it possible to make money trading using
price action alone?

197
00:14:38,040 --> 00:14:39,040
Sure.

198
00:14:39,040 --> 00:14:42,680
But price in combination with volume is 10
times better.

199
00:14:42,680 --> 00:14:48,079
First, you see what the CANDLESTICK is telling
you, then you check the volume, and see if

200
00:14:48,079 --> 00:14:51,320
it’s validating or not with the recent price
action.

